description: Require [DAY-N] commit prefix when branch contains DAY<digits> (e.g., feat/zhanna-DAY9-someFeature)
alwaysApply: true
---

# Commit messages: DAY branch prefix

When suggesting or writing a **git commit message**, first inspect the current branch name.

If the branch contains `DAY` followed by digits anywhere in the name (regex: `DAY(\d+)`), the commit subject line **must start** with the matching tag in this exact form:

- `DAY4` -> `[DAY-4]`
- `DAY5` -> `[DAY-5]`
- `DAY10` -> `[DAY-10]`
- `feat/zhanna-DAY9-someFeature` -> `[DAY-9] ...`

Use a **hyphen** after `DAY`: `[DAY-N]`. Do not use `[DAY9]`, `DAY-9: ...`, or omit the prefix.

**Examples**

- Branch `feat/zhanna-DAY5-addedMarkAsStudiedAtTheBottom-DEVELOP`  
  Good: `[DAY-5] feat(study): show code examples on study guide`  
  Bad: `feat(study): show code examples` (missing prefix when branch encodes DAY5)

- Branch `feat/some-DAY4-feature`  
  Good: `[DAY-4] fix: handle edge case`

- Branch `feat/zhanna-DAY9-someFeature`  
  Good: `[DAY-9] feat(plan): add sticky Study Guide button`
  Bad: `feat(plan): add sticky Study Guide button`

If the **current branch name** does not contain any `DAY{digits}` segment, do **not** add this prefix unless the user explicitly asks.

When multiple `DAY` segments appear (rare), use the **last** or most specific one the user is clearly working on; if unclear, prefer the highest-numbered day or ask.
